"Yao S.L., Okumoto M., Nakayama A., Suzuki E.","Plasma reforming and coupling of methane with carbon dioxide",2001,"Energy and Fuels","15","5",,"1295","1299",,,10.1021/ef010089+,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035437694&partnerID=40&md5=fc07247ee164c8f602a9a4171a0ab67f","Catalysis Science Laboratory, Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth, 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizu-cho, Soraku-gun, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan","Yao, S.L., Catalysis Science Laboratory, Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth, 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizu-cho, Soraku-gun, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Okumoto, M., Catalysis Science Laboratory, Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth, 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizu-cho, Soraku-gun, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Nakayama, A., Catalysis Science Laboratory, Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth, 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizu-cho, Soraku-gun, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Suzuki, E., Catalysis Science Laboratory, Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth, 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizu-cho, Soraku-gun, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan","Plasma reforming and coupling of methane with carbon dioxide using a point-to-point type of reactor have been invested. A feed mixture of CH4 and CO2 could be converted mainly to CO, H2, and C2H2 at atmospheric pressure and without external heating except plasma heating. Under a condition of 200 mL/min of CH4 and CO2 (CH4:CO2 volume ratio, 50:50), a 2.5 mm discharge gap, and a pulse frequency of 10.3 kPPS, CH4 and CO2 conversion, CO and C2H2 selectivities, H2/CO ratio, and (CH4 + CO2) conversion efficiency were 65.9% and 57.8%, 85.9% and 11.3%, 0.99, and 2.4 mmol/kJ, respectively. C2H2 selectivity and H2/CO ratio could be moderated by changing CH4 concentration in the feed mixture. The influence of methane concentration and pulse frequency on product selectivity and plasma energy efficiency was evaluated. A brief economic evaluation of this process was given. The coproduction of acetylene of high value remarkably improved the production of synthesis gas (CO + H2) from carbon dioxide reforming of methane, which could also contribute the emission reduction of global warming gas CO2.",,"Plasma energy; Atmospheric pressure; Carbon dioxide; Catalysts; Concentration (process); Plasma heating; Methane",,,,,,"Poirier, M.G., Trudel, J., Guay, D., (1993) Catal. Lett., 21, p. 99; Chang, Y.F., Heineman, H., (1993) Catal. Lett., 21, p. 215; Tsang, S.C., Claridge, J.B., Green, M.L.H., (1995) Catal. Today, 23, p. 3; Wang, S., Lu, G.Q., Millar, G.J., (1996) Energy Fuels, 10, p. 896; Bradford, M.C.J., Vannice, M.A., (1996) J. Catal., 142, p. 73; Ross, J.R.H., Van Keulen, A.N.J., Hegarty, M.E.S., Seshan, K., (1996) Catal. Today, 30, p. 193; Bitter, J.H., Seshan, K., Lercher, J.A., (1998) J. Catal., 176, p. 93; O'Connor, A.M., Ross, J.R.H., (1998) Catal. Today, 46, p. 203; Bradford, M.C.J., Vannice, M.A., (1999) Catal. Today, 50, p. 87; Tsui, M., Miyao, T., Naito, S., (2000) Catal. Lett., 69, p. 195; Fischer, F., Tropsch, H., (1928) Brennstoff Chem., 9, p. 39; Solbakken, A., (1991) Natural Gas Conversion, p. 447. , Holmen, A., et al., Eds. Elsevier Science Publisher: Amsterdam; Keller, G.E., Bhasin, M.M., (1982) J. Catal., 73, p. 9; Matherne, J.L., Culp, G., (1990) AIChE, Ann. Meeting, , Chicago, paper 59f; Lee, L.L., Aitani, A.M., (1991) Fuel Sci. Int., 9 (2), p. 137; Mallinson, R.G., Sliepcevich, C.M., Rusek, S., (1987) Am. Chem. Soc., Div. Fuel Chem., 32, p. 266; Bhatnagar, R., Mallison, R.G., (1995) Methane and Alkane Conversion Chemistry, p. 249. , Bhasin, M. M., Slocum; D. W., Eds.; Plenum Press: New York; Liu, C.G., Marafee, A., Hill, B.J., Xu, G.H., Mallinson, R., Lobban, L., (1996) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 35 (10), p. 3295; Larkin, D.W., Caldwell, T.A., Lobban, L.L., Mallinson, R.G., (1998) Energy Fuels, 12, p. 740; Larkin, D.W., Lobban, L.L., Mallinson, R.G., (2000) 1st International Conference on Gas Processing, p. 10. , AIChE Spring National Meeting, GA, Mar